<br>
I'm assuming you aren't one of these serious enchanters, and I would further assume you haven't talked to one of them recently.  The &quot;nerf&quot; of affliction focus items makes charming a bit more difficult, although definitely not impossible, solo, and leaves the difficulty-level about the same in groups.<br>
<br>
Btw, the enchanter boards apparently are private -- Verant certainly isn't looking there with any regularity or it wouldn't have taken them the better part of a year to fix the affliction items. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Apparently some newbie enchanters who probably aren't of level enough to actually cast PoP charms, actually believe the anti-nerf propoganda posted on the chanter forums. I guess thats an unforseen sideeffect of the anti-nerf campaign.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
One only needs Boltran's (low-50's charm) to realize the power of charm in PoP (and one only needs to make it to the mid-teens to realize the power of charm.)  Granted, it's advantage isn't quite as clearly delineated to Boltran's users as that of CoD, but the scale is easily seen.  Charm is powerful.  It's also risky.<br>
<br>
Overpowered?  I don't know.  I know quite a few solo 65 necro's who aren't lagging behind aa per unit of time with far less risk.  The factoring of resists (virtually non-existant) and short duration charms (much more existant,) deaths, downtime attributed to untimely charm breaks, pathing issues, and other deterimental conditions rarely take their place in the evaluation of charm by non-enchanters.  While it's easy to dismiss the claims of the enchanter who says &quot;No, it's not,&quot; it's also quite easy for those who aren't enchanters not to know what they're talking about.  Point being, the area is far more gray than you imply.  Perhaps the frustration some of the enchanter community feels is because they aren't considered 'serious' if what they feel doesn't correspond to what non-enchanters feel a 'serious' enchanter would believe. <br>
<br>
It doesn't really matter to me what they do to charm (although I'm partial to just making charms exempt from any focus effects.)  I'll still be charming one way or the other, and mostly in groups.  Soloing bores me.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If verant undid the manaburn nerf, and made it mana-free, with a 10 second recast timer, it would be _less_ powerful than charm (though admittedly easier to use and more flexible).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The two really aren't comparable. There is no risk associated with manaburn.  I don't think anything will ever be (or ever has been) as powerful as charm in the situations where it can be useful.<br>
<br>
Fallacy Rampant - 62 enchanter (CT)<br>
