<br>
Compare that to the 900dps pets. I mean really, I saw 3 mages and 4 clerics and 2 enchanters kill emmerik skyfury(they had to pull pets back repeatedly with the portals down. 10 person kill. do people kill dain with 10?). The other guys just watched this bare minimum go and see if it could do it. I also checked into bastion of thunder the other day and watched a group from my guild go at it. Almsot the entire Sand wing of the zone had been cleared, I was able to navigate to them by following the corpses almost where sand started to close to the lord.<br>
<br>
This death thing doesn't seem to be much of a factor anymore, but a skill thing. At least this is so for the mages of my guild. The group previously mentioned I had checked with and watched for some kills. They didn't wipe for the 2 1/2 hours I'd checked with them, and using /time /time it was about 20 seconds to kill something, as in 2 minutes I saw 6 mobs pulled &amp; killed. I also grouped with a mage who died to a charm break once in 40 bot lord kills in about a week(no competition on kb) using muzzle/burnout haste.<br>
<br>
I haven't paid this much attention but this is what I'm getting at; this risk business is based largely on player skill. You can have a paladin or wizard stun a tashed pet on charm break and mage can gank it back. Quadding is similar, too. I'll admit that I die a lot less than these runs- actually one legitimate quadding death(non ld/crash/tech) in halls of honor in these 80aa spent at the spot when I was cutting it really close and got stuck for a half second on one of those rectangular prism things and the whole quad suddenly ran into my back - a feeble ~4800hps at that time for 500hitters - stunned and splatted me. When a wizard dies, he's got to drag a cleric or eat death, then find someone to VOQ or KEI him which of course is different than a group taking much longer than the setup for a group. But it also is a matter of skills- when youve quadded for long enough, I guess death can become something you don't run into very often. Same for some of the people I see charming. When they first go at it the GY in bot will be flooded with that mage's nude corpses. People experienced with charming I group with rarely die around their pet, and it's generally hasted.<br>
<br>
Later on I don't see many deaths, and checking with them confirms that. As for 'one' zone stuff... It's all you need at level 65, one zone. Having that limit hasn't prevented people from doing crazy aaxp... or basing all of their xping off of charm. None of what anyone has ever told me has indicated that charm is actually balanced. A good and practiced mage can make himself into a tDPS machine of 400 given deaths etc, from what I've seen. A 300 AA rogue with moderate ssra(guess) equip(basically someone taken over by my regular group as a bot who also raided but basically quit) was 153dps(72 seconds)s in this parse on most stuff, while Braan frienai was 654dps(70 seconds) and even had the charm drop midfight, though mage recharmed. I didn't even have to stun it.<br>
<br>
Obviously what you can do with charm way outperforms what anybody else can do. I would think that's unbalanced as there's people who, with some practice, are taking the sustained longer term tdps range to 300-400 when the next melee is not able to go over 200! <br>
<br>
Then again I got my strike of solusek while using charmed mobs to kill a named a long time back. I've benefitied from it but I am a fan of balance- and the devs are too I'd think by now. There can't be any question as to whether or not this is overpowered. I have seen what good mages/enc do with this, and if you can't power past a 'well formed'(pre pop) regular group, then I would assume you're not good at this. Even if it's not brought in line with wizards, look at rogues:<br>
<br>
They can't melee an AE ramping mob. Outdone by rangers there.<br>
Rogues don't outdamage me on raids, scratch high raid DPS.<br>
With graveyards, rogues aren't needed for CR.<br>
In groups, the sustained dps of a good mage parsed has been around 300-400. Since rogue dmg is pretty pathetic compared to this, I don't see a lot of them grouped so don't have good figures. Still, 37-50% as good dmg as a mage.<br>
<br>
While not picking on rogues, I'm looking for some sort of benchmark here. They used to be what was the top sustained dps, often doubling over wizards in graphs. Now if everything is balanced, someone explain to me what a rogue is the best for in POP, other than moving around and not getitng aggro. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=goladus>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<br>Err, Forum Arch Mage?</span><br>  Posts: 3375<br> <font color=#ffffff>(2/21/03 6:11:06 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm53.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=227.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://doug.feldmann.com/Sigurd.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Mage dps with charm</span><hr size=1> Honestly I could care less about charm soloing.  The ability to solo may or may not be a consequence of an overpowered ability.<br>
