<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I gave it a parse. Based on if the hits did not crit, but were not resisted, my dps in HOH quadding is 410dps when a quad is up out of about 540 possible. With flowing thought 15 allegiant flappy horse dagger of entrapment etc I'll finish that quad at 25-40% mana. That's with VOQ. At ~12 minutes realistically to a quad this is about 104,000hp dealt for 145dps.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->410 dps is very high.  And at 12 minutes to a quad, that's 20 mobs per hour.  I can't imagine that you'd be getting any less than 2% xp per mob, in fact I think 3% would be a good lowball guess.  I'll guess at 2.3% for a compromise.  At 20 mobs per hour, your rate of aa gain is 1 aa every 2 hours, 10 minutes.  If you have a problem with that <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">solo</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> I'm sorry go cry me a fucking river <br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :sosad --><img src=http://rombusmindspire.tripod.com/sosad.txt ALT=":sosad"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Compare that to the 900dps pets.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->That would be an interesting comparison to see.  One which you do not show us.  Every time charm breaks, that lowers its dps.  General downtime must be considered as well.  Without including that your 900dps quotes mean exactly nothing up your quadding numbers.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I mean really, I saw 3 mages and 4 clerics and 2 enchanters kill emmerik skyfury(they had to pull pets back repeatedly with the portals down. 10 person kill. do people kill dain with 10?).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->While I have issues with the raid encounters that I may address if I have time, the number of people used to kill Dain has absolutely nothing to do with the number of people used to kill a BoT mob.  They are different mobs, the strategies used to kill them are supposed to be different.  And how is Dain supposed to be a fair comparison?  Dain is the boss of his zone.  You want the boss of BoT go say hi to Agnarr.  Skyfury is a gimp Agnarr sycophant.  Besides I would not be surprised to see 10 people kill Dain.  Just people don't want to because Dain sucks.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>This death thing doesn't seem to be much of a factor anymore, but a skill thing. At least this is so for the mages of my guild. The group previously mentioned I had checked with and watched for some kills. They didn't wipe for the 2 1/2 hours I'd checked with them, and using /time /time it was about 20 seconds to kill something, as in 2 minutes I saw 6 mobs pulled &amp; killed. I also grouped with a mage who died to a charm break once in 40 bot lord kills in about a week(no competition on kb) using muzzle/burnout haste<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Yes but you can't write it off as a factor when babbling on about 900dps pets.  You need to give all factors their appropriate weight.  Assuming that charm-breaking is an ultimate balance factor is a mistake, but totally writing off its effects is equally problematic.<br>
<br>
But yes the 20 second kills are compelling.  I do believe charmed pets that can outtank any melee while doing the dps of a whole group are overpowered.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I haven't paid this much attention but this is what I'm getting at; this risk business is based largely on player skill. You can have a paladin or wizard stun a tashed pet on charm break and mage can gank it back. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Yes.. but note that the player skill also involves player coordination.  Players working together is a good thing.  There should be more to the game than just mob-hits-tank, cleric-heals-tank, damagers-damage, chanters-buff-mez.  The issue is if relatively few people that need to work together to achieve far more than should be possible.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Later on I don't see many deaths, and checking with them confirms that. As for 'one' zone stuff... It's all you need at level 65, one zone.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Indeed, I think this actually adds to the problem.  Charm can accomplish so much in BoT that people never want to xp anywhere else.  <br>
<br>
Fleshing out this argument is critical.  Everyone should have situations where they are more powerful than others, but no ability should be so powerful that it causes whole groups to leech off that one skill for far more xp/loot than could be earned otherwise.  Not that I blame anyone for taking advantage of charm as it exists.  Not in the slightest.  I think it's the natural thing to do.  Unfortunately I think it is bad for the game.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>A good and practiced mage can make himself into a tDPS machine of 400 given deaths etc, from what I've seen.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This doesn't sound too unrealistic to me, either.  But then it's also not limited to mages.  It's charm in general.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>They can't melee an AE ramping mob. Outdone by rangers there.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I am no expert but I'm told that AE rampage can be dealt with in ways other than simply having all the melees sit aside.<br>
<br>
One seperate issue when it comes to melees, is that charmed pets cannot hold aggro over melees, which makes melee useless in such fights.  That is a huge problem that needs to be addressed <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">before</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> any changes get made to charm.<br>
